<paper id="1966612958"><title>Spacefilling curves and the planar travelling salesman problem</title><year>1989</year><authors><author org="Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta" id="204967837">Loren K. Platzman</author><author org="Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta" id="2275525160">John J. Bartholdi</author></authors><n_citation>125</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>1994507531</reference><reference>2007147155</reference><reference>2055569927</reference><reference>2145535767</reference></references><venue id="118992489" type="J">Journal of the ACM</venue><doi>10.1145/76359.76361</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.45544">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.45445">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.48848">Heuristic</keyword><keyword weight="0.50041">Sorting</keyword><keyword weight="0.42183">Planar</keyword><keyword weight="0.58504">Travelling salesman problem</keyword><keyword weight="0.48785">Time complexity</keyword><keyword weight="0.40684">Mathematics</keyword></keywords><publisher>ACM</publisher><abstract>To construct a short tour through points in the plane, the points are sequenced as they appear along a spacefilling curve. This heuristic consists essentially of sorting, so it is easily coded and requires only O ( N ) memory and O ( N log N ) operations. Its performance is competitive with that of other fast methods.</abstract></paper>